The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, May 21, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, May 20: The Reserve Bank of India will monitor the liquidity conditions in the financial markets closely whenever circuit filters in stock exchanges are activated. The central bank had taken pro-active measures to improve liquidity when the capital market crashed on Monday by lowering margin requirements. The RBI is believed to have set up a committee that will closely monitor the liquidity conditions in the bond, money and forex markets.																								 New Delhi, May 20: Air France today became the first international carrier to hike its fares from India by 3 euro, citing a steep rise in aviation turbine fuel prices as the reason which may also force Indian carriers to follow suit.																								 New Delhi, May 20: The cellular operators have decided to lower the roaming tariffs for certain slabs to bring them in line with the prescribed ceiling. This follows a directive issued by the Telecom Regulatory Authority of India on this issue.																								 New Delhi, May 20: AirTel today announced its talktime transfer service enabling its pre-paid subscribers to transfer talktime from one mobile to another.																								 Mumbai, May 20: Deepak Fertilisers and Petrochemicals Co Ltd has reported an 8.75 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 69.72 crore for the year ended March 31, 2004 compared with Rs 64.11 crore in the previous fiscal.
